== Service histories ==
[[File:USS Arizona in New York City Crisco edit.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|''Arizona'' on the East River in New York City near the Brooklyn Bridge, 1918. Photograph <span class="plainlinks">[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/hhh.hi0096/photos.184205p courtesy]</span> of the Library of Congress.]]
''Pennsylvania'' and ''Arizona'' were commissioned during the [[World War I|First World War]], but prior to the [[American entry into World War I|United States' entry]] on the side of the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]]. During their first year, the ships were cleaned and readied for full active duty.<ref>Stillwell, ''Battleship Arizona'', 13<U+2013>17.</ref> ''Pennsylvania'' became the [[flagship]] of the US Atlantic Fleet on 12 October 1916.<ref>"''Pennsylvania''", ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships''.</ref> ''Arizona'' first fired its main guns on 23 December, but issues with the propulsion system, specifically a stripped turbine, kept the ship almost exclusively in the New York Navy Yard from December 1916 to March 1917.<ref>Stillwell, ''Battleship Arizona'', 18<U+2013>21.</ref> Both ships were based in the United States for the duration of the war, owing to a shortage of fuel oil in the United Kingdom, and only the coal-burning battleships of [[United States Battleship Division Nine (World War I)|Battleship Division Nine]] were sent.<ref>Jones, ''Battleship Operations'', 28, 92.</ref> After the [[Armistice with Germany|armistice]], both ''Pennsylvania''-class battleships were sent to the other side of the Atlantic. ''Arizona'' was sent first, leaving on 18 November and arriving in Portsmouth on the 30th. ''Pennsylvania'' escorted the American President [[Woodrow Wilson]]'s transport, {{ship|SS|George Washington||2}}, across the Atlantic for the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] in 1919.<ref>Stillwell, ''Battleship Arizona'', 37<U+2013>38; Jones, ''Battleship Operations'', 106.</ref> In 1921 and 1922, during the [[inter-war period]], both ships took part in a mission to Peru and were transferred to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]].<ref>"''Pennsylvania''" and "''Arizona''", ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships''.</ref>

''Pennsylvania'' and ''Arizona'' were given extensive modernizations from 1929 through 1931; the expenditure came in the fiscal year 1930.<ref>Friedman, ''U.S. Battleships'', 191, 197.</ref> As part of the rebuilding, ''Pennsylvania'', which had been designed as a fleet flagship, had its conning tower expanded. Aside from that, ''Pennsylvania'' and ''Arizona'' received similar treatment: the elevation of the main batteries was increased to {{degree|30}}, new fire control systems on [[tripod mast]]s were added, the secondary armament and directors were replaced and overhauled (with the five-inch guns being moved into their own twin mounts), and their bridges were enlarged to hold elevated antiaircraft directors. Armor additions were comparatively minimal beyond [[anti-torpedo bulge]]s, which were standard additions on all major warships in this period: {{convert|1.75|to|2|in|mm}} of armor were added to the second [[deck (ship_|armored deck]], and a [[torpedo bulkhead]] was added to the engine room. The propulsion system of the two ''Pennsylvania''s received perhaps the most attention. The boiler system was entirely replaced with six small-tube boilers and new turbines, the latter partially from the canceled {{sclass-|South Dakota|battleship (1920)|0}} battleship {{USS|Washington|BB-47|2}}. The new machinery allowed the ships to come close to their old design speed of {{convert|21|kn|mph km/h}}, even with the added bulk of bulges: ''Pennsylvania'' made 20.89&nbsp;knots and ''Arizona'' 20.7&nbsp;knots on full-power trials.<ref>Friedman, ''U.S. Battleships'', 197<U+2013>201.</ref>

After their modernization, both ships participated in the normal activities of the fleet, including [[fleet problem]] exercises, and then joined the entire Pacific Fleet in their new base in [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Hawaii]], after the beginning of the Second World War in Europe. Two years later, on 7 December 141, the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] sank ''Arizona'' in a tremendous explosion and slightly damaged ''Pennsylvania'', which was in dry dock at the time.<ref>Stillwell, ''Battleship Arizona'', 274<U+2013>76; Whitley, ''Battleships'', 262; "''Pennsylvania''" and "''Arizona''", ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships''.</ref>

[[File:US warships entering Lingayen Gulf 1945.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|The now-famous photograph of ''Pennsylvania'' leading {{USS|Colorado|BB-45|2}} and three cruisers into [[Lingayen Gulf]] before the [[Battle of Luzon|invasion of Luzon]] (Philippines), in January 1945. Photograph <span class="plainlinks">[http://arcweb.archives.gov/arc/action/ExternalIdSearch?id=52062 courtesy]</span> of the National Archives and Records Administration.]]
''Pennsylvania'' came back into service more quickly than many of the other battleships present during the attack; it left on 20 December and was under repair in San Francisco until 30 March 1942. For the next several months, ''Pennsylvania'' was stationed on the United States' [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]], before being reassigned to Pearl Harbor as the fleet flagship for a short time (August to October). After another refit in San Francisco, which lasted until February 1943, the ship was sent to assist American forces engaged in the [[Aleutian Islands Campaign]]. During this time, ''Pennsylvania'' was nearly hit by a torpedo from {{Jsub|I-31}}, which was later sunk.<ref>Whitley, ''Battleships'', 262.</ref>

For the next year, ''Pennsylvania'' was utilized in shore bombardment in the Battles of [[Battle of Makin|Makin]], [[Battle of Kwajalein|Kwajalein]], [[Battle of Eniwetok|Eniwetok]], and [[Battle of Saipan|Saipan]], along with the [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign|Palau Islands Campaign]]. The ship also participated in the [[Battle of Leyte|landings on Leyte]] and the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]]. During this time, ''Pennsylvania'' was present at the last battle ever between battleships, the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf#The Battle of Surigao Strait (25 October)|Battle of Surigao Strait]]. The ship did not fire any salvos because the Japanese vessels were turned away or sunk at long range, beyond ''Pennsylvania''{{'}}s outdated fire control but within range of other, radar-directed battleships.<ref>Whitley, ''Battleships'', 262<U+2013>63.</ref>

In 1945, ''Pennsylvania'' was sent for another refit in San Francisco, and the guns in its main battery, worn out from the frequent shore bombardments, were replaced by those from ''Nevada'' and ''Oklahoma''. After its completion in July, the ship bombarded [[Wake Island]] on 1 August en route to Okinawa, where it was struck by an air-dropped torpedo. It hit near the starboard propeller shaft, killing twenty men and knocking out three of the ship's four shafts. The area near the shafts, though, was also a vital area, and the opened seals around the shafts led to large amounts of flooding that nearly sank the battleship. ''Pennsylvania'' was towed to shallower waters, where local repairs were made. The ship's last action was to fire at a ''[[kamikaze]]'' on 13 August, before it was towed to Guam beginning on the 18th, where temporary repairs were effected, before it was sent to Puget Sound for more permanent repairs. ''Pennsylvania'' arrived on 24 October only after a torturous journey, which saw the ship lose all but one of its remaining propeller shafts while taking on water through the temporary patch put over the torpedo hole in Guam.<ref>Whitley, ''Battleships'', 263; Cates, ''War History'', 37<U+2013>38.</ref>

With the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] on 2 September, the Puget Sound repairs were limited to those necessary to ensure ''Pennsylvania''{{'}}s delivery to [[Bikini Atoll]] for [[Bikini atomic experiments|atomic experiments]] in July 1946. The old battleship survived the tests, but was decommissioned on 29 August and used for [[radiation|radiological]] studies before being sunk as a [[target ship]] on 10 February 1948. ''Pennsylvania'' was struck from the [[Navy Vessel Register]] nine days later.<ref>Whitley, ''Battleships'', 263; Cates, ''War History'', 38; "[http://www.nvr.navy.mil/nvrships/details/BB38.htm Pennsylvania (BB 38)]," ''[[Naval Vessel Register]]''.</ref>

